00:04:33.183 --> 00:04:35.190
and such practical effects.

00:04:35.190 --> 00:04:37.360
And it's so, so cool to
see that brought back.

00:04:37.360 --> 00:04:40.140
It's really like an old
film thing that really

00:04:40.140 --> 00:04:41.440
is replaced by CGI these days.

00:04:41.440 --> 00:04:43.990
So that was really important
for you to really have in there.

00:04:43.990 --> 00:04:48.120
So did that take some convincing
of executive producers at all

00:04:48.120 --> 00:04:49.715
to go that route versus the CG?

00:04:49.715 --> 00:04:51.090
SETH MACFARLANE:
I mean, it was--

00:04:51.090 --> 00:04:53.910
you can't do it for
the entire series.

00:04:53.910 --> 00:04:54.810
It's too costly.

00:04:54.810 --> 00:04:58.560
But for things like flybys
that you use every week, where

00:04:58.560 --> 00:05:01.980
it's just establishing shots of
the ship, it actually becomes--

00:05:01.980 --> 00:05:02.830
it's twofold.

00:05:02.830 --> 00:05:04.680
It becomes economically
helpful, because you

00:05:04.680 --> 00:05:06.390
can reuse these same shots.

00:05:06.390 --> 00:05:10.920
And it just looks, you know,
it's actual light hitting

00:05:10.920 --> 00:05:13.230
an actual surface, which is--

00:05:13.230 --> 00:05:15.810
it is still-- particularly
on a television budget,

00:05:15.810 --> 00:05:17.790
it is still hard
to duplicate that.

00:05:17.790 --> 00:05:19.580
I mean, and our team
does a great job.

00:05:19.580 --> 00:05:21.350
They have fooled
me more than once.

00:05:21.350 --> 00:05:23.630
But I don't know.

00:05:23.630 --> 00:05:26.220
