00:05:35.310 --> 00:05:39.529
and you can touch it is to
me, I figure this is probably

00:05:39.529 --> 00:05:41.820
the last time I'm ever going
to be able to do something

00:05:41.820 --> 00:05:42.778
like this in my career.

00:05:42.778 --> 00:05:45.390
Because everything
is going to CGI.

00:05:45.390 --> 00:05:49.237
So it was a privilege to work
with somebody like Rob Legato,

00:05:49.237 --> 00:05:50.820
too, who I've been
a fan of for years.

00:05:50.820 --> 00:05:51.640
KEVIN BELK: That's so neat.

00:05:51.640 --> 00:05:53.900
And so for the writers, do
you guys when you guys--

00:05:53.900 --> 00:05:55.110
when you guys come
into the show,

00:05:55.110 --> 00:05:56.370
and then when you got
onto the show, do you

00:05:56.370 --> 00:05:58.140
guys find yourself
kind of backed up

00:05:58.140 --> 00:05:59.390
against the wall a
little bit sometimes,

00:05:59.390 --> 00:06:01.050
where it's we want to do
this, but it's either not

00:06:01.050 --> 00:06:02.883
in the budget, or we
don't have this set up.

00:06:02.883 --> 00:06:05.670
Or how does it work with kind
of getting into the production

00:06:05.670 --> 00:06:08.340
process and storytelling?

00:06:08.340 --> 00:06:10.590
LIZ HELDENS: You know, we've
worked on TV for a while,

00:06:10.590 --> 00:06:12.600
so you sort of understand when
you're breaking a story what

00:06:12.600 --> 00:06:15.131
the limits are in terms of
what you can do on a television

00:06:15.131 --> 00:06:15.630
budget.

00:06:15.630 --> 00:06:18.660
But what do you sort of
see on this show, I think,

00:06:18.660 --> 00:06:21.990
is you see people
like Joseph and Howard

00:06:21.990 --> 00:06:24.010
who bring their A game in a way.

00:06:24.010 --> 00:06:26.300
So you're seeing
costumes and you're

00:06:26.300 --> 00:06:27.990
seeing makeup that
you really don't

00:06:27.990 --> 00:06:31.710
see on other really
television shows.

00:06:31.710 --> 00:06:36.090
But yet this show is within
the budget of a normal show.

00:06:36.090 --> 00:06:37.420
And that same with our-

00:06:37.420 --> 00:06:39.589
BRANNON BRAGA: This episode
was a great example.

00:06:39.589 --> 00:06:40.380
Those aliens were--

00:06:40.380 --> 00:06:41.860
DAVID A. GOLDEN: You want
to answer it, is that it?

00:06:41.860 --> 00:06:43.620
BRANNON BRAGA: Well, you
weren't you weren't answering it

00:06:43.620 --> 00:06:43.890
correctly.

00:06:43.890 --> 00:06:44.160
[LAUGHTER]

00:06:44.160 --> 00:06:45.284
DAVID A. GOLDEN: All right.

00:06:47.250 --> 00:06:49.880
I thought this was
a great example of--

00:06:49.880 --> 00:06:54.110
the script did not describe
what the aliens looked like,

00:06:54.110 --> 00:06:57.612
and these guys created something
amazing and very memorable.

00:07:00.850 --> 00:07:02.309
KEVIN BELK: Liz,
how about for you?

00:07:02.309 --> 00:07:04.683
Particularly with this episode,
when you were writing it,

00:07:04.683 --> 00:07:06.270
did you work heavily
with Seth on it?

00:07:06.270 --> 00:07:07.387
How did that work?

00:07:07.387 --> 00:07:09.470
LIZ HELDENS: We all broke
the episode in the room.

00:07:09.470 --> 00:07:14.570
And then we pretty much--

00:07:14.570 --> 00:07:17.240
it was a pretty thorough break.

00:07:17.240 --> 00:07:19.790
And then I just went
away and wrote it.

00:07:19.790 --> 00:07:21.480
And then Seth fixed it.

00:07:21.480 --> 00:07:24.100
And then, now we're here.

00:07:24.100 --> 00:07:26.306
SETH MACFARLANE: I
don't have to fix much.

00:07:26.306 --> 00:07:28.520
We're begging her to
come back for season two.

00:07:28.520 --> 00:07:30.950
LIZ HELDENS: But I don't
feel like in the room that

00:07:30.950 --> 00:07:35.580
there's ever any, I don't know,
Seth creates a pretty nice

00:07:35.580 --> 00:07:37.400
space that I don't--

00:07:37.400 --> 00:07:39.660
I mean, for me, I
never feel limitations.

00:07:39.660 --> 00:07:41.970
I always feel like
the story comes first,

00:07:41.970 --> 00:07:44.860
the characters come first, and
then we'll figure it out later.

00:07:44.860 --> 00:07:46.440
KEVIN BELK: And what's the
lead time for a lot of this?

00:07:46.440 --> 00:07:47.940
Because it's
actually really crazy

00:07:47.940 --> 00:07:51.529
to see each episode almost
get more and more complicated.

00:07:51.529 --> 00:07:53.070
Especially when the
Krill episode was

00:07:53.070 --> 00:07:53.980
the first time that I really--

00:07:53.980 --> 00:07:55.770
BRANNON BRAGA: This
is highly unusual.

00:07:55.770 --> 00:07:57.607
Every script's
written ahead of time.

00:07:57.607 --> 00:07:58.940
LIZ HELDENS: Yeah, it's so nice.

00:07:58.940 --> 00:08:01.630
BRANNON BRAGA: Which
just rarely happens.

00:08:01.630 --> 00:08:03.510
So when we go into
production, the scripts

00:08:03.510 --> 00:08:08.997
have been written and
vetted to a thorough degree.

00:08:08.997 --> 00:08:11.580
KEVIN BELK: Is that because of
the production time with makeup

00:08:11.580 --> 00:08:14.081
and costumes and the wardrobe
and set making and everything?

00:08:14.081 --> 00:08:16.663
DAVID A. GOLDEN: Actually, this
was sort of driven by the fact

00:08:16.663 --> 00:08:18.760
that Seth wanted to be
in the writers' room.

00:08:18.760 --> 00:08:21.660
And usually a star of a
show, if you're shooting,

00:08:21.660 --> 00:08:23.910
he wouldn't have been able
to be in the writers' room.

00:08:23.910 --> 00:08:26.584
So last year we wrote
all the scripts,

00:08:26.584 --> 00:08:28.500
and that gave us a lot
of flexibility in terms

00:08:28.500 --> 00:08:30.640
of laying out the season.

00:08:30.640 --> 00:08:32.220
SETH MACFARLANE:
It's also, like, you

00:08:32.220 --> 00:08:35.460
know, again, I haven't worked
in hour long live action

00:08:35.460 --> 00:08:36.429
television before.

00:08:36.429 --> 00:08:40.110
And the idea of shooting
something and spending

00:08:40.110 --> 00:08:43.169
12 to 14 hours a day
and killing yourself

00:08:43.169 --> 00:08:45.870
to get it done on a
TV shooting schedule

00:08:45.870 --> 00:08:48.690
and having it be something
that you haven't polished

00:08:48.690 --> 00:08:53.430
to the point at which, you
know, the work is as good as you

00:08:53.430 --> 00:08:59.157
can do, I don't think I could
make it through the day.

00:08:59.157 --> 00:09:00.240
Well, this is good enough.

00:09:00.240 --> 00:09:03.164
Now let's all stay here
14 hours filming it.

00:09:03.164 --> 00:09:04.330
No, you want it to be great.

00:09:04.330 --> 00:09:04.890
KEVIN BELK: Right.

00:09:04.890 --> 00:09:06.431
I mean, so you worked
in live action,

00:09:06.431 --> 00:09:10.275
obviously, before with
"Ted" and "A Million Ways

00:09:10.275 --> 00:09:13.460
to Die in the West," and now
with "Family Guy" and "American

00:09:13.460 --> 00:09:13.960
Dad."

00:09:13.960 --> 00:09:15.960
So what did you learn
from that previous work

00:09:15.960 --> 00:09:17.459
that you brought
to this that helped

00:09:17.459 --> 00:09:22.370
you just get through the process
a little bit better and easier?

00:09:22.370 --> 00:09:24.900
SETH MACFARLANE: Well, you
know, certainly VFX integration

00:09:24.900 --> 00:09:27.249
is something that, with
"Ted," was, I mean,

00:09:27.249 --> 00:09:28.290
that was the whole movie.

00:09:28.290 --> 00:09:31.140
Was you're working with a
character who's not there,

00:09:31.140 --> 00:09:35.620
and you have to shoot the scene
with a guy who's not there.

00:09:35.620 --> 00:09:38.430
So that was certainly
a big part of it.

00:09:38.430 --> 00:09:39.570
But it's also the planning.

00:09:39.570 --> 00:09:41.834
And dealing with a show
like "Family Guy," you know,

00:09:41.834 --> 00:09:42.750
it's an animated show.

00:09:42.750 --> 00:09:46.157
So you don't do coverage.

00:09:46.157 --> 00:09:48.490
You don't get this shot, then
this shot, then this shot.

00:09:48.490 --> 00:09:51.480
You get the shot that you
planned for, and that's it.

00:09:51.480 --> 00:09:53.730
So that's something,
coming out of animation

00:09:53.730 --> 00:09:56.660
and going into visual
effects, heavy stuff,

00:09:56.660 --> 00:09:58.230
is kind of helpful.

00:09:58.230 --> 00:10:03.270
Because you do have to decide
before you even do the work.

00:10:03.270 --> 00:10:04.451
OK, this is the shot.

00:10:04.451 --> 00:10:06.700
You're not going to get to
cut to something different.

00:10:06.700 --> 00:10:08.700
And put, like, this is
the special effects shot.

00:10:08.700 --> 00:10:16.650
So animation conditions
you to work, making sure

00:10:16.650 --> 00:10:19.680
that you're not going to change
your mind later on, that you

00:10:19.680 --> 00:10:21.439
know how to plan scenes.

00:10:21.439 --> 00:10:22.230
KEVIN BELK: Gotcha.

00:10:22.230 --> 00:10:24.330
We were watching that
featurette video, too,

00:10:24.330 --> 00:10:29.306
for the wardrobe and makeup,
so let's take a look at that.

