When we first started
designing things,

00:11:00.020 --> 00:11:01.114
all I had was the script.

00:11:01.114 --> 00:11:02.780
The descriptions were
different than how

00:11:02.780 --> 00:11:03.821
the creatures turned out.

00:11:03.821 --> 00:11:05.030
Bortus had a big evolution.

00:11:05.030 --> 00:11:07.440
The initial design process
was pretty long for Bortus.

00:11:07.440 --> 00:11:09.470
It was at least a
five month period.

00:11:09.470 --> 00:11:12.125
Once Peter Aiken was hired,
we brought him into KNB,

00:11:12.125 --> 00:11:13.320
and we life cast him.

00:11:13.320 --> 00:11:15.361
So we had his head, and
we could sculpt on that.

00:11:15.361 --> 00:11:17.360
And we went through a
couple different versions.

00:11:17.360 --> 00:11:18.680
We never quite hit it.

00:11:18.680 --> 00:11:21.267
I came down here, set up
a little sculpting area,

00:11:21.267 --> 00:11:22.850
and I just sat and
sculpted for, like,

00:11:22.850 --> 00:11:24.350
three or four hours with Seth.

00:11:24.350 --> 00:11:26.900
And we finally hit on
what Bortus's look was.

00:11:26.900 --> 00:11:29.180
We went ahead, and we
designed it pretty simple.

00:11:29.180 --> 00:11:31.670
Peter would come in the morning,
and we'd get him prepped.

00:11:31.670 --> 00:11:34.416
And there was a cowl, and
his face would be exposed.

00:11:34.416 --> 00:11:36.290
And then we'd glue his
chin on, and then he'd

00:11:36.290 --> 00:11:37.581
have a whole front of the face.

00:11:37.581 --> 00:11:41.060
What remains Peter is this whole
area here and his eye area.

00:11:41.060 --> 00:11:43.220
And the pieces are very
soft, and they were thin,

00:11:43.220 --> 00:11:45.025
so he was able to
maneuver his face.

00:11:45.025 --> 00:11:46.400
The first time we
had done it, we

00:11:46.400 --> 00:11:47.600
had him sit in
front of the mirror

00:11:47.600 --> 00:11:49.460
and just move around
and do expressions.

00:11:49.460 --> 00:11:51.865
You have to exaggerate
your facial expressions

00:11:51.865 --> 00:11:53.990
to some degree, and Peter
was really great with it.

00:11:53.990 --> 00:11:55.400
And as a makeup
designer, you want that.

00:11:55.400 --> 00:11:57.830
You don't want to have this
giant makeup on somebody,

00:11:57.830 --> 00:11:59.150
and they can't act.

00:11:59.150 --> 00:12:00.962
He's just such a
great actor, and he

00:12:00.962 --> 00:12:02.170
brought that make up to life.

00:12:02.170 --> 00:12:03.610
[APPLAUSE]

00:12:03.610 --> 00:12:10.810
[END PLAYBACK]

00:12:10.810 --> 00:12:13.340
KEVIN BELK: So how did you
convince Peter to do this,

00:12:13.340 --> 00:12:15.680
that you're going to come
in every day for 14 hours

00:12:15.680 --> 00:12:18.044
and wear this heavy
makeup or [INAUDIBLE]..

00:12:18.044 --> 00:12:19.210
HOWARD BERGER: It was tough.

00:12:19.210 --> 00:12:20.760
But he is so great, though.

00:12:20.760 --> 00:12:21.530
He was in for it.

00:12:21.530 --> 00:12:25.730
He's one of those actors
who, he understood

00:12:25.730 --> 00:12:29.840
what the process was, and that's
half the battle right there.

00:12:29.840 --> 00:12:32.630
We do our job in the
morning, myself and Tami Lane

00:12:32.630 --> 00:12:33.980
and Garrett Immel.

00:12:33.980 --> 00:12:36.830
And he goes through two hours
of makeup every day, probably

00:12:36.830 --> 00:12:39.170
applied it like 60
or 70 times, I think,

00:12:39.170 --> 00:12:40.880
through the course of the shoot.

00:12:40.880 --> 00:12:44.450
And he was always, always
there, and let us do our job,

00:12:44.450 --> 00:12:46.610
and then he went to set
and brought it to life.

00:12:46.610 --> 00:12:48.110
And that takes a lot, you know.

00:12:48.110 --> 00:12:50.900
He never complained, was
really, like, the easiest guy

00:12:50.900 --> 00:12:52.260
to deal with.

00:12:52.260 --> 00:12:54.920
KEVIN BELK: Joseph, how about
for you, with costuming,

00:12:54.920 --> 00:12:56.210
wardrobes in there?

00:12:56.210 --> 00:12:59.240
What was the most difficult part
or the most exciting part also

00:12:59.240 --> 00:13:01.115
for you when you were
creating these costumes

00:13:01.115 --> 00:13:03.920
and the main design
for the flight crew?

00:13:03.920 --> 00:13:07.130
JOSEPH PORRO: Well, the alien
stuff they saw in this episode,

00:13:07.130 --> 00:13:09.500
I can do that in my sleep.

00:13:09.500 --> 00:13:11.800
The crazy stuff is easy.

00:13:11.800 --> 00:13:15.490
The uniform, and it's
still a work in progress.

00:13:15.490 --> 00:13:16.861
We're still tweaking it.

00:13:16.861 --> 00:13:18.860
I don't know if I'll ever
be happy with it, even

00:13:18.860 --> 00:13:22.170
on season 7, I'll probably
be doing something.

00:13:22.170 --> 00:13:24.920
But that was the biggest
challenge for me.

00:13:24.920 --> 00:13:29.990
And it's just these
high tech fabrics.

00:13:29.990 --> 00:13:31.690
When you're used to
building suits out

00:13:31.690 --> 00:13:35.580
of wool, which form to the
body really beautifully,

00:13:35.580 --> 00:13:37.255
and then you get a
high tech sneaker

00:13:37.255 --> 00:13:39.380
fabric, which is actually
what they're made out of.

00:13:39.380 --> 00:13:40.880
We had them all
custom made for us

00:13:40.880 --> 00:13:45.230
in China, these fabrics
for these uniforms.

00:13:45.230 --> 00:13:48.170
So that was, I'd say,
the biggest challenge.

00:13:48.170 --> 00:13:50.870
And it's an ongoing work.

00:13:50.870 --> 00:13:55.670
But it's-- in eight
days, for him to pull,

00:13:55.670 --> 00:13:57.567
and for me to-- we
have eight days.

00:13:57.567 --> 00:13:58.400
That's what we have.

00:13:58.400 --> 00:13:59.709
HOWARD BERGER: That's it.

00:13:59.709 --> 00:14:00.500
JOSEPH PORRO: Whoa.

00:14:00.500 --> 00:14:01.769
[LAUGHTER]

00:14:01.769 --> 00:14:03.310
JOSEPH PORRO: Well,
it's not just us.

00:14:03.310 --> 00:14:05.510
I mean, I'm sure that's
every other department, too.

00:14:05.510 --> 00:14:07.970
But what's great
about this show,

00:14:07.970 --> 00:14:11.360
and you guys can't see this
when you watch the episode,

00:14:11.360 --> 00:14:15.320
is behind the camera is one
of the best groups of people

00:14:15.320 --> 00:14:17.600
I've worked in in 35 years.

00:14:17.600 --> 00:14:21.290
We actually like all our actors.

00:14:21.290 --> 00:14:24.220
They actually like us.

00:14:24.220 --> 00:14:26.900
And everyone says excuse
me if you do something.

00:14:26.900 --> 00:14:28.700
You know, it's just--

00:14:28.700 --> 00:14:31.640
so we all are kind of psyched
to go in in the morning.

00:14:31.640 --> 00:14:34.001
We really look forward
to getting up at 4:30.

00:14:34.001 --> 00:14:34.834
HOWARD BERGER: Yeah.

00:14:34.834 --> 00:14:37.890
[LAUGHTER]

00:14:37.890 --> 00:14:39.292
JOSEPH PORRO: Enough.

00:14:39.292 --> 00:14:41.750
KEVIN BELK: Well, I mean, when
you were building this crew,

00:14:41.750 --> 00:14:43.791
and you worked with a lot
of these people before?

00:14:43.791 --> 00:14:47.270
Liz, David, Brannon, you guys
worked together before right?

00:14:47.270 --> 00:14:48.247
No?

00:14:48.247 --> 00:14:49.580
DAVID A. GOLDEN: Brannon and I--

00:14:49.580 --> 00:14:50.900
I worked for Brannon on
one of the "Star Trek."

00:14:50.900 --> 00:14:51.525
KEVIN BELK: OK.

00:14:51.525 --> 00:14:54.500
DAVID A. GOLDEN: But we'd
never worked with Liz before.

00:14:54.500 --> 00:14:56.785
JOSEPH PORRO: I worked
with Brannon on "Next Gen."

00:14:56.785 --> 00:14:57.770
He doesn't remember me.

00:14:57.770 --> 00:14:58.510
[LAUGHTER]

00:14:58.510 --> 00:15:00.230
JOSEPH PORRO: On
season 1, and then

00:15:00.230 --> 00:15:02.410
I did Salem with
him for three years.

00:15:02.410 --> 00:15:04.070
KEVIN BELK: And then what were
some of your guys' influences,

00:15:04.070 --> 00:15:05.960
I guess, when you're
putting together the show?

00:15:05.960 --> 00:15:08.030
What, maybe when you were
growing up or whatever,

00:15:08.030 --> 00:15:09.290
when you're designing
this, and you're coming up

00:15:09.290 --> 00:15:11.580
with the story and stuff,
what influenced you as a kid

00:15:11.580 --> 00:15:14.729
to [INAUDIBLE] this
and create the series?

00:15:14.729 --> 00:15:16.520
SETH MACFARLANE: I
mean, for me, obviously,

00:15:16.520 --> 00:15:19.634
I remember watching
the stuff that Brannon

00:15:19.634 --> 00:15:20.800
had written for "Star Trek."

00:15:20.800 --> 00:15:23.800
I mean, there's this great,
great, thoughtful science

00:15:23.800 --> 00:15:25.840
fiction.

00:15:25.840 --> 00:15:28.330
But you know, god, I
mean, I was also a big fan

00:15:28.330 --> 00:15:29.470
of "The Twilight Zone."

00:15:29.470 --> 00:15:31.053
I watched things
like "Night Gallery."

00:15:31.053 --> 00:15:33.970
Like, anything I
could find where

00:15:33.970 --> 00:15:41.980
I was being told a story that
would keep me up that night.

00:15:41.980 --> 00:15:46.724
I remember reading a Stephen
King story called "The Jaunt."

00:15:46.724 --> 00:15:48.140
I think it was in
"Skeleton Crew."

00:15:48.140 --> 00:15:50.200
And it kept me up
for, like, two days.

00:15:50.200 --> 00:15:51.950
This just blew my mind.

00:15:51.950 --> 00:15:54.700
And that's the
kind of stuff that,

00:15:54.700 --> 00:15:58.570
in writing science fiction,
that I kind of look for.

00:15:58.570 --> 00:16:05.690
Is something that just sits with
me, you know, like a bad meal.

00:16:05.690 --> 00:16:10.170
And you know, it's tricky.

00:16:10.170 --> 00:16:11.830
And also to make
it human, to make

00:16:11.830 --> 00:16:16.660
it something that feels like
it can exist in the real world,

00:16:16.660 --> 00:16:20.680
and is not so exotic that
it doesn't take you out

00:16:20.680 --> 00:16:24.010
of this kind of day
to day office life

00:16:24.010 --> 00:16:25.385
that we're also
trying to create.

00:16:25.385 --> 00:16:27.343
KEVIN BELK: And we'll
kind of go down the line.

00:16:27.343 --> 00:16:30.400
But who were your influences,
Liz, when you were growing up

00:16:30.400 --> 00:16:32.250
and got you into the
[INAUDIBLE] you do?

00:16:32.250 --> 00:16:34.583
LIZ HELDENS: Yeah, I knew you
were going to ask me that.

00:16:34.583 --> 00:16:35.740
KEVIN BELK: Sorry.

00:16:35.740 --> 00:16:37.570
LIZ HELDENS: I watched
"Next Generation."

00:16:37.570 --> 00:16:39.340
I watched "Star Trek."

00:16:39.340 --> 00:16:42.010
And then I kind of put
that away and watched,

00:16:42.010 --> 00:16:44.214
you know, me in my
20s, I just watched

00:16:44.214 --> 00:16:45.380
what everybody else watched.

00:16:45.380 --> 00:16:47.950
Like, you know, I just
watched all the HBO stuff.

00:16:47.950 --> 00:16:51.700
And then, when
this job came up, I

00:16:51.700 --> 00:16:53.690
had forgotten all about
"Star Trek Next Gen,"

00:16:53.690 --> 00:16:56.050
and then I found it again.

00:16:56.050 --> 00:16:57.680
And it was great.

00:16:57.680 --> 00:17:02.617
But I don't come
from, I mean, the work

00:17:02.617 --> 00:17:05.200
that I've done, I mean, the work
that I've done as a writer is

00:17:05.200 --> 00:17:07.270
not like genre stuff.

00:17:07.270 --> 00:17:09.490
Like, I come from
"Friday Night Lights"

00:17:09.490 --> 00:17:15.299
and super like feely,
feely emotional shows.

00:17:15.299 --> 00:17:15.909
[LAUGHTER]

00:17:15.909 --> 00:17:17.700
KEVIN BELK: This has
some of that in there.

00:17:17.700 --> 00:17:18.785
LIZ HELDENS: No,
it totally does.

00:17:18.785 --> 00:17:19.150
SETH MACFARLANE: It does.

00:17:19.150 --> 00:17:19.983
But I think that's--

00:17:19.983 --> 00:17:23.550
I mean that's what to me
you want in that room.

00:17:23.550 --> 00:17:25.589
I mean, ideally, you
know, you want people

00:17:25.589 --> 00:17:28.260
in that room who don't come
from a sci-fi background

00:17:28.260 --> 00:17:32.350
as well, who just are fucking
great at writing people.

00:17:32.350 --> 00:17:34.030
And you've got to have that.

00:17:34.030 --> 00:17:35.430
JOSEPH PORRO: I am a designer.

00:17:35.430 --> 00:17:37.570
So I do files.

00:17:37.570 --> 00:17:39.960
So I go, I'm all
through deviant art

00:17:39.960 --> 00:17:41.760
and all these crazy websites.

00:17:41.760 --> 00:17:42.590
And I'm looking--

00:17:42.590 --> 00:17:44.506
SETH MACFARLANE: What
are your favorite drugs?

00:17:44.506 --> 00:17:45.159
[LAUGHTER]

00:17:45.159 --> 00:17:45.950
JOSEPH PORRO: True.

00:17:52.500 --> 00:17:53.840
The late '60s [INAUDIBLE].

00:17:53.840 --> 00:17:56.400
HOWARD BERGER: That's true.

00:17:56.400 --> 00:17:59.030
KEVIN BELK: Fair enough.

00:17:59.030 --> 00:18:00.114
How about for you, Howard?

00:18:00.114 --> 00:18:01.988
HOWARD BERGER: Yeah,
for me, it was I grew up

00:18:01.988 --> 00:18:03.130
on monsters and movies.

00:18:03.130 --> 00:18:06.060
So I grew up with the
classic universal monsters.

00:18:06.060 --> 00:18:09.390
And then TV was "Twilight
Zone" and "Night Gallery,"

00:18:09.390 --> 00:18:10.230
absolutely.

00:18:10.230 --> 00:18:12.900
The green thumb one is the one
that got me, when they cut off,

00:18:12.900 --> 00:18:13.720
and they--

00:18:13.720 --> 00:18:16.350
and still scary.

00:18:16.350 --> 00:18:18.330
But just loved
monsters and films.

00:18:18.330 --> 00:18:20.820
And about eight
years old, I knew

00:18:20.820 --> 00:18:23.100
I was going to grow up and
make monsters for movies.

00:18:23.100 --> 00:18:25.320
And I just worked towards
that my entire life.

00:18:25.320 --> 00:18:28.080
And you know, this is one of
the many great opportunities

00:18:28.080 --> 00:18:30.510
I've had in my 35
year career now.

00:18:30.510 --> 00:18:33.690
So it's definitely one of the
most fun things I've ever done.

00:18:33.690 --> 00:18:38.580
JOSEPH PORRO: You know, him and
I did our first show together,

00:18:38.580 --> 00:18:41.730
my first show as a designer,
first show of his makeup,

00:18:41.730 --> 00:18:42.750
back in the mid-'80s.

00:18:42.750 --> 00:18:43.320
SETH MACFARLANE: Was what?

00:18:43.320 --> 00:18:44.700
JOSEPH PORRO: I'm not going
to tell you the name of it.

00:18:44.700 --> 00:18:45.283
It's horrible.

00:18:45.283 --> 00:18:47.700
HOWARD BERGER: It's
called "Neon Maniacs."

00:18:47.700 --> 00:18:49.160
I was 18 years old.

00:18:49.160 --> 00:18:50.970
Yeah, it was-- it's
a real-- it's great.

00:18:50.970 --> 00:18:51.470
JOSEPH PORRO: But it was--

00:18:51.470 --> 00:18:53.511
HOWARD BERGER: Yeah, it
just came out on Blu-ray.

00:18:56.760 --> 00:18:59.030
JOSEPH PORRO: Let's
go back to 1980.

00:18:59.030 --> 00:18:59.530
[INAUDIBLE]

00:18:59.530 --> 00:19:01.363
SETH MACFARLANE: I'll
take your word for it.

00:19:01.363 --> 00:19:02.230
[LAUGHTER]

00:19:02.230 --> 00:19:03.480
KEVIN BELK: David and Brannon?

00:19:03.480 --> 00:19:06.040
DAVID A. GOLDEN: I watched
five hours of television a day.

00:19:06.040 --> 00:19:07.860
So whatever was on.

00:19:07.860 --> 00:19:12.660
Every sitcom, I was a big "Star
Trek" fan, giant, huge giant,

00:19:12.660 --> 00:19:14.160
geek "Star Trek" fan.

00:19:14.160 --> 00:19:18.780
But sitcoms were also a big
part of what we watched at home.

00:19:18.780 --> 00:19:21.294
And I became a sitcom
writer because of that.

00:19:21.294 --> 00:19:23.460
SETH MACFARLANE: David wrote
for "The Golden Girls."

00:19:23.460 --> 00:19:24.418
He won't tell you that.

00:19:24.418 --> 00:19:27.919
[APPLAUSE]

00:19:27.919 --> 00:19:29.460
DAVID A. GOLDEN: I
don't bring it up,

00:19:29.460 --> 00:19:31.418
because I was also fired
by "The Golden Girls."

00:19:31.418 --> 00:19:34.150
[LAUGHTER]

00:19:34.150 --> 00:19:36.420
KEVIN BELK: And Brannon?

00:19:36.420 --> 00:19:40.240
BRANNON BRAGA: Any horror movie
I could sneak into as a kid.

00:19:40.240 --> 00:19:40.990
I liked horror.

00:19:40.990 --> 00:19:44.274
I was a big horror fan.

00:19:44.274 --> 00:19:45.690
KEVIN BELK: So
audience questions,

00:19:45.690 --> 00:19:48.400
I'm going to pass around this.

00:19:48.400 --> 00:19:48.900
Where is it?

00:19:48.900 --> 00:19:50.190
Oh, right here, here we go.

00:19:52.297 --> 00:19:53.880
SETH MACFARLANE:
Google is not stuffy,

00:19:53.880 --> 00:19:55.690
like those other companies.

00:19:55.690 --> 00:19:57.149
AUDIENCE: We throw
our microphones.

00:19:57.149 --> 00:19:58.940
It's like, yeah, you
just can't see my face

00:19:58.940 --> 00:19:59.880
on that [INAUDIBLE].

00:19:59.880 --> 00:20:01.024
Anyway--

00:20:01.024 --> 00:20:02.440
SETH MACFARLANE:
Now everyone else

00:20:02.440 --> 00:20:03.260
is going to want to touch that.

00:20:03.260 --> 00:20:04.218
AUDIENCE: Yeah, I know.

00:20:04.218 --> 00:20:06.090
[LAUGHTER]

00:20:06.090 --> 00:20:07.530
AUDIENCE: Thank you so much.

00:20:07.530 --> 00:20:08.310
This is awesome.

00:20:08.310 --> 00:20:11.230
We really appreciate it.

00:20:11.230 --> 00:20:13.320
So you guys do
realize that you've

00:20:13.320 --> 00:20:17.460
made a better "Star Trek" than
all modern "Star Trek," right?

00:20:17.460 --> 00:20:20.712
Like, this is a really,
really amazing experience

00:20:20.712 --> 00:20:21.420
going through it.

00:20:21.420 --> 00:20:23.790
This is actually the first
episode that I've seen,

00:20:23.790 --> 00:20:26.820
and now I'm going to rush home
and watch everything else.

00:20:26.820 --> 00:20:30.030
But the question I
have is, how did you

00:20:30.030 --> 00:20:33.030
go about getting network
approval to actually get this?

00:20:33.030 --> 00:20:34.770
Because in my mind,
you have to, like,

00:20:34.770 --> 00:20:38.190
admit some pheromone from
your body to go to Fox

00:20:38.190 --> 00:20:39.222
and get this done?

00:20:39.222 --> 00:20:41.430
So I'm curious, like, what
that approval looked like?

00:20:41.430 --> 00:20:42.810
What was the pushback?

00:20:42.810 --> 00:20:44.190
What did you sort
of, like, where

00:20:44.190 --> 00:20:45.780
was that happy
medium that you had

00:20:45.780 --> 00:20:47.640
to reach to get this approved?

00:20:47.640 --> 00:20:49.889
SETH MACFARLANE: You know,
it wasn't really that hard.

00:20:49.889 --> 00:20:53.250
I mean, Fox, in particular, the
way it was communicated to me,

00:20:53.250 --> 00:21:00.180
they had been trying to find a--

00:21:00.180 --> 00:21:02.760
"Guardians of the
Galaxy" had been a hit,

00:21:02.760 --> 00:21:04.350
the resurgence of "Star Wars."

00:21:04.350 --> 00:21:06.870
They'd been trying
to find a sci-fi show

00:21:06.870 --> 00:21:09.450
with a comedic element
that would work for them.

00:21:09.450 --> 00:21:11.490
And it's a hard thing to do.

00:21:11.490 --> 00:21:13.447
And generally, it's
done in the half hour

00:21:13.447 --> 00:21:15.780
format, which I always feel
like is part of the problem.

00:21:15.780 --> 00:21:19.170
Because you're already
one step removed

00:21:19.170 --> 00:21:22.710
from reality, and
to me, the trick

00:21:22.710 --> 00:21:26.862
was all right, keep
leaning into the comedy,

00:21:26.862 --> 00:21:28.070
and so it's making it harder.

00:21:28.070 --> 00:21:29.986
If we leaned a little
bit more into the drama,

00:21:29.986 --> 00:21:31.922
and let the comedy
just be garnish,

00:21:31.922 --> 00:21:33.130
then maybe that's the answer.

00:21:33.130 --> 00:21:35.460
But it really wasn't
that difficult. I mean,

00:21:35.460 --> 00:21:37.110
they were excited by the idea.

00:21:37.110 --> 00:21:39.000
They felt like it was different.

00:21:39.000 --> 00:21:41.160
They liked that it was
episodic, because everything

00:21:41.160 --> 00:21:42.310
is serialized now.

00:21:42.310 --> 00:21:46.200
And on a network, I
think, look, if it's

00:21:46.200 --> 00:21:47.850
Netflix, if it's
Amazon, if it's Hulu,

00:21:47.850 --> 00:21:51.650
and you're getting
everything in one big chunk,

00:21:51.650 --> 00:21:55.500
and you can binge watch
it, then it's great.

00:21:55.500 --> 00:21:57.540
It's hard for me,
sometimes, to invest fully

00:21:57.540 --> 00:21:59.576
in serialized
programming on a network,

00:21:59.576 --> 00:22:01.200
because I got to wait
a week, you know?

00:22:01.200 --> 00:22:05.100
I want to be told an isolated,
independent story, Rod Serling

00:22:05.100 --> 00:22:06.139
