00:24:20.910 --> 00:24:23.140
as opposed to a sailing
ship is something

00:24:23.140 --> 00:24:28.695
that emerged from science
fiction prior, from the 1930s,

00:24:28.695 --> 00:24:29.320
from the 1940s.

00:24:29.320 --> 00:24:31.194
I mean, there were other
shows that did that.

00:24:31.194 --> 00:24:34.880
But they really were
the ones that kind of

00:24:34.880 --> 00:24:37.042
put a memorable stamp on it.

00:24:37.042 --> 00:24:39.000
And so the tricky thing
is, all right, anything

00:24:39.000 --> 00:24:45.000
you do that deals with a
crew on a spaceship traveling

00:24:45.000 --> 00:24:47.970
through space, you're
working in that territory.

00:24:47.970 --> 00:24:54.200
And "Star Trek" and "Star
Wars" have trodden those paths

00:24:54.200 --> 00:24:57.300
so heavily that
it is a challenge.

00:24:57.300 --> 00:25:01.970
And so my solution
was really not to try

00:25:01.970 --> 00:25:05.030
and twist myself into a
pretzel trying to all right,

00:25:05.030 --> 00:25:06.710
you know, maybe, you
know, trying to do

00:25:06.710 --> 00:25:08.000
something so exotic and new.

00:25:08.000 --> 00:25:09.458
I just kind of
embraced, all right,

00:25:09.458 --> 00:25:10.660
this is a bridge of a ship.

00:25:10.660 --> 00:25:12.260
It's a crew on a spaceship.

00:25:12.260 --> 00:25:13.010
Let's start there.

00:25:13.010 --> 00:25:15.680
What can we do that's
new from that point.

00:25:15.680 --> 00:25:17.750
And a lot of it was tone.

00:25:17.750 --> 00:25:22.724
A lot of it was the thing of
putting the two command chairs

00:25:22.724 --> 00:25:24.890
next to each other with the
captain and the ex-wife,

00:25:24.890 --> 00:25:28.220
instantly turns this into--

00:25:28.220 --> 00:25:31.040
it's now you're getting
into "Cheers" territory,

00:25:31.040 --> 00:25:32.660
and that I haven't seen.

00:25:35.600 --> 00:25:38.020
